The paper deals with fair division and mechanism design, which are topics commonly studied in the field of computational game theory (cs.GT). The algorithms presented in the paper involve computational techniques such as network flows, convex programming, and randomization, which are relevant to the subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of algorithms in decision-making and optimization, which are relevant to the subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The concepts of fairness and Pareto optimality are central to the subfield of computational economics (cs.EC), and the paper presents algorithms that aim to achieve these goals. Finally, the paper discusses the use of algorithms in mechanism design, which is a topic studied in the subfield of multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
